# Design System - Use Existing Components

## 🎯 The Rule

When implementing any UX pattern, **strongly prefer existing design system components** over building from scratch.

## What Counts as a Design System Component

A component is part of the design system if it meets **either** of these criteria:

- **(a) Located in `components/morph/`** — shared product components (e.g. `Tag`, `Tooltip`, `Button`, `Card`, `Drawer`, `Dialog`)
- **(b) Has a Ladle story** — any component with a `*.stories.tsx` file next to it (e.g. `Button.stories.tsx`, `Tag.stories.tsx`)

## Using Design System Components

When you find a relevant component:

- **Read its Ladle story** (`*.stories.tsx`) first — it documents available props, variants, and intended usage
- **Check 2–3 existing product uses** (grep for the component's import) to see real-world configuration patterns

## Navigating UX patterns that aren't supported by the design system

If the user requests a UX pattern that the existing design system components **don't support**, say so explicitly before proceeding:

> "The existing `[ComponentName]` component doesn't support [X]. I can either extend it or build a custom implementation — which would you prefer?"

Do **not** silently build a one-off custom component when a design system component almost fits. Surface the gap so the user can decide.
